# Verify moth tokens in your backend

moth signs every access token with the project's ES256 key. Your API
verifies them offline against the project JWKS — no call to moth on the
request path.

| Value | |
| --- | --- |
| JWKS URL | `{{.JWKSURL}}` |
| Expected `iss` | `{{.Issuer}}` |
| Expected `aud` | `{{.Audience}}` |
| Algorithm | `ES256` (reject everything else) |

`payload.sub` is the moth user id — use it as the stable foreign key in
your own database.

## Node (jose)

```js
import { createRemoteJWKSet, jwtVerify } from "jose";

const jwks = createRemoteJWKSet(new URL("{{.JWKSURL}}"));

export async function verifyMothToken(token) {
  const { payload } = await jwtVerify(token, jwks, {
    issuer: "{{.Issuer}}",
    audience: "{{.Audience}}",
  });
  return payload; // payload.sub is the moth user id
}
```

## Go (lestrrat-go/jwx)

```go
import (
	"context"

	"github.com/lestrrat-go/jwx/v3/jwk"
	"github.com/lestrrat-go/jwx/v3/jwt"
)

var cache, _ = jwk.NewCache(context.Background(), nil)

func init() {
	cache.Register(context.Background(), "{{.JWKSURL}}")
}

func verifyMothToken(ctx context.Context, raw string) (jwt.Token, error) {
	keys, err := cache.Lookup(ctx, "{{.JWKSURL}}")
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	return jwt.Parse([]byte(raw),
		jwt.WithKeySet(keys),
		jwt.WithIssuer("{{.Issuer}}"),
		jwt.WithAudience("{{.Audience}}"),
	)
}
```

## Dart backend (package:jose)

```dart
import 'package:jose/jose.dart';

Future<Map<String, dynamic>> verifyMothToken(String token) async {
  final jwt = await JsonWebToken.decodeAndVerify(
    token,
    JsonWebKeyStore()..addKeySetUrl(Uri.parse('{{.JWKSURL}}')),
  );
  final claims = jwt.claims;
  if (claims.issuer != Uri.parse('{{.Issuer}}') ||
      !(claims.audience?.contains('{{.Audience}}') ?? false)) {
    throw Exception('token was not minted for this app');
  }
  return claims.toJson();
}
```

## Online introspection (instant revocation checks)

When you need revocation to take effect immediately (offline JWTs stay
valid until expiry, default 15 minutes), ask moth instead. Requires the
project's **secret key** (`sk_...`, shown once at project creation;
rotate with `moth project keys regenerate-secret --show-secret`):

```sh
grpcurl \
  -H 'x-moth-key: sk_YOUR_SECRET_KEY' \
  -d '{"access_token": "eyJ..."}' \
  MOTH_GRPC_HOST:443 \
  moth.server.v1.TokenService/IntrospectToken
```

Expected: `{"active": true, "userId": "...", ...}`; a revoked or expired
token returns `"active": false`. Generate a typed client for any language
from the served proto sources:
`{{.Endpoint}}/protos/moth/server/v1/token.proto` (plus
`.../moth/auth/v1/auth.proto` and `.../moth/server/v1/user.proto`).

## Failure modes

| Symptom | Fix |
| --- | --- |
| JWKS URL returns 404 | Wrong project slug in the URL — the exact URL is in `moth project keys show {{.Slug}}` and on the Setup page |
| `kid` not found in JWKS | The signing key was reset (`moth project keys reset-signing`) — refetch the JWKS; old tokens are permanently invalid |
| `aud`/`iss` mismatch | Token comes from another project or instance; expected values are in the table above |
| Valid signature but stale claims | Verify expiry (`exp`) and, for instant revocation, use IntrospectToken |
